(237, 237, 1, 'The Rise of Thirsty Cities', 'the-rise-of-thirsty-cities', 'news/2019/12/5e0b0da387678.jpg', 'A new report suggests global data underestimates the urban water crisis.', '<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\"><em><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"color: #111111;\"><img style=\"width: 700px; height: 467px;\" src=\"/pic/News/images/EN028.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></span></span></em></span></span></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\"><em><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"color: #111111;\">Workers fill wagons of a train with drinking water en route to Chennai, India, in July.</span></span></em></span></span></div>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><br /><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\"><strong><span style=\"text-transform: uppercase;\"><span style=\"color: #111111;\">IT MAY SEEM&nbsp;</span></span></strong><span style=\"color: #111111;\">counterintuitive given the headlines about&nbsp;water-strapped cities&nbsp;like Chennai, India and Cape Town, South Africa, but there was once a time when Victoria Beard\'s research on water scarcity was dismissed as unnecessary.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"color: #111111;\">\"People would say, \'Why would you do a paper on water access in cities? It\'s not a problem anymore,\" says Beard, a fellow at the World Resources Institute.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"color: #111111;\">But according to a recent paper she coauthored, the problem is not only still here, but likely to get worse.</span><br /><span style=\"color: #111111;\">Global data underestimates the urban water crisis, contributing to ineffective management and planning by city leaders, according to a&nbsp;new report&nbsp;by the WRI Ross Center for Sustainable Cities. The report, \"Unaffordable and Undrinkable: Rethinking Urban Water Access in the Global South,\" is the latest in a series of recent studies warning about the link between climate change and dwindling global resources.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"color: #111111;\">While water scarcity isn\'t solely an urban problem, with 68% of the world\'s population expected to live in cities by 2050, it will be an inescapable reality for many municipalities. In 2015, less than half of the urban population in many countries was receiving piped water, the report found. If city leaders don\'t act, authors argue climate change and population growth could lead to \"day zero\" for many more cities in developing countries.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"color: #111111;\">Beard says that after the deadline for the U.N. Millennium Development Goals expired in 2015, many in the international development field were optimistic about the gains made to address water access.</span><br /><span style=\"color: #111111;\">But while there was indeed real progress, she says the way international organizations were measuring water access was too broad, with a lack of attention to water quality, regularity and affordability. In the end, the findings pointed to a picture that was far rosier than what Beard and other researchers were encountering on the ground.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"color: #111111;\">\"All of us who work in Africa, South Asia and Southeast Asia and other parts of the global South, we thought \'These don\'t actually represent what\'s happening in the cities we work on,\'\" says Beard, a professor of urban planning at Cornell University. \"They draw attention away from the crisis.\"</span><br /><br /><span style=\"color: #111111;\">Although the U.N. reports that the proportion of the population with access to improved water sources has increased globally, the portion of urban residents receiving piped water has decreased since 1990, according to the report. When water is pumped through continuously, access to a piped network provides the cheapest and safest water access.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"color: #111111;\">\"The lack of understanding of the scale and the scope of the urban water crisis in the global South inhibits meaningful action on the part of urban change agents; as a result, cities are failing to take the steps necessary to ensure equitable water access,\" according to the report.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"color: #111111;\">Researchers focused on 15 cities in Latin America, Africa and Southeast Asia. They found Latin America had the highest proportion of water piped to a home or a yard, followed by South Asia and Africa. Only three cities in their sample &ndash; Colombo, Sri Lanka; S&atilde;o Paulo, Brazil; and Santiago de Cali, Colombia &ndash; reported having continuous piped water supplies. Continuous water is important to water quality because when pressure in a piped network drops, sewage, groundwater and other contaminants can enter the system.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"color: #111111;\">The report makes a financial argument for addressing water scarcity. While the World Health Organization reports that investing in universal drinking water in urban areas would cost $141 billion over five years, the report argues the total economic and environmental cost of inaction amounts to $260 billion a year.</span><br /><br /><span style=\"color: #111111;\">To prevent the growth of thirsty cities, the report suggests governments and water utilities take the following steps:</span></span></span></div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"margin-top: 0in; margin-right: 0in; margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: #111111;\">Expand formal piped water networks to increase access.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"margin-top: 0in; margin-right: 0in; margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: #111111;\">Address intermittent water service to allow businesses and individuals to anticipate their water access and plan effectively.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"margin-top: 0in; margin-right: 0in; margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: #111111;\">Pursue an array of strategies, like offering subsidies for water, to reduce the cost of water for low-income residents.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"margin-top: 0in; margin-right: 0in; margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: #111111;\">Work within informal settlements to upgrade infrastructure and improve water access to the urban under-served.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: #111111;\">\"We feel that a lot of cities are not being proactive in terms of the investment and planning that needs to take place,\" Beard says. \"Without cities taking the actions in our paper, I expect that this problem will get worse.\"</span><br />&nbsp;<br /><span style=\"font-size: 12px;\"><em>Reporter: <span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"color: #111111;\">Devon Haynie</span></span></em><br /><em><span style=\"background-image: initial; background-position: initial; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial;\"><span style=\"color: #111111;\">Source: https://www.usnews.com/news/cities/articles/2019-08-13/a-new-urban-crisis-lack-of-water</span></span></em></span></span></span></div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'news', 1, NULL, 0, 'vi', 3, '0', '2019-09-16 09:35:00', 1, '2019-12-31 08:58:28', 1, '2019-12-31 08:58:28', NULL),
